          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What was Yugoslavia?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-9-3.jpg" alt="What was Yugoslavia?" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Yugoslavia-former-federated-nation-1929-2003" target="_blank">Yugoslavia</a> was a country in Southeast Europe that existed from 1918 to 2003. It was initially formed after World War I as the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes, later renamed the Kingdom of Yugoslavia in 1929. After World War II, it became a socialist federation, officially called the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, under the leadership of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Josip-Broz-Tito" target="_blank">Josip Broz Tito</a>.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Yugoslavia was a multi-ethnic and multi-religious federation made up of six republics: Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, Montenegro, Serbia, and Slovenia. Despite its official unity, ethnic tensions and nationalism were always present, leading to political and social instability.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The country began to <a href="https://history.state.gov/milestones/1989-1992/breakup-yugoslavia" target="_blank">untangle</a> in the 1990s due to ethnic tensions, economic problems, and the rise of nationalist movements. This resulted in a series of conflicts, and by the early 2000s, Yugoslavia had dissolved into several independent countries: Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, North Macedonia, Montenegro, and Serbia, with Kosovo declaring independence in 2008 (though it is not universally recognized). Yugoslavia’s legacy is still felt in the cultural dynamics of the Balkans, where issues of ethnic identity, national borders, and the aftermath of war continue to shape the region’s history.​</p>
        </mj-text>
